## 1. Introduction

Keeping release notes accurate and timely is tedious: developers must collect PR descriptions, commits, and changelogs, then craft readable summaries. This guide shows how to Build an AI release notes generator with GitHub Actions so your repository can automatically generate human-readable release notes from PRs and commits. You'll get an end-to-end pattern, code samples, and best practices to deploy a safe, maintainable pipeline.

What you'll gain:
- A reproducible GitHub Actions workflow that triggers on release or merge.
- A script that collects commit/PR metadata, calls an LLM to summarize changes, and publishes release notes.
- Practical tips for prompts, rate limits, and security.

## 2. What is Build an AI release notes generator with GitHub Actions?

At its core, this is an automated pipeline that:
- Gathers change data (commits, merged PRs, labels, authors).
- Constructs a prompt describing the changes.
- Sends the prompt to a language model (via an API) to produce concise human-friendly release notes.
- Publishes the generated notes as a GitHub Release or attaches them to a changelog file.

Analogy: think of it as a smart editor sitting between your Git history and your release page — it reads the raw changes and writes a clear summary.

Related tools and ecosystem:
- GitHub Actions (CI automation).
- GitHub REST API / Octokit (fetch PR and release data).
- An LLM provider (for example, OpenAI API or other provider you configure).
- Optional: existing tools like Release Drafter (for templated drafts) — this approach augments templates with AI summarization.

## 3. Why It Matters

Developer pain points this solves:
- Time-consuming manual release notes.
- Inconsistent style and missing context in changelogs.
- Hard-to-scan release pages for non-dev stakeholders.

Real-world relevance:
- Teams often skip detailed release notes when time is limited, which increases support burden and slows onboarding. Automating the summarization step reduces friction while keeping humans in the loop for final edits.

Industry context:
- Many teams use CI to automate packaging and publishing; adding AI summarization integrates seamlessly with existing CI/CD practices without changing developer workflows.

## 4. How It Works (Technical Overview)

Core components and flow:
1. Trigger: on push to main, on push with tags, or on release creation (GitHub Actions event).
2. Collector: gather commits and merged PRs between the last release tag and the new commit/tag using GitHub API or `git`.
3. Prompt builder: format collected data (titles, bodies, labels, authors) into a compact prompt.
4. LLM call: call the LLM API with the prompt and small instructions to produce structured release notes (sections like Features, Fixes, Breaking changes).
5. Publisher: create or update a GitHub Release, append to CHANGELOG.md, or open a pull request with the generated notes.

Architecture diagram (conceptual):

- GitHub Actions -> Collector (Node/Python script) -> LLM API -> Publisher (GitHub Release / PR)

Permissions and secrets:
- GITHUB_TOKEN (for GitHub REST API calls).
- OPENAI_API_KEY or equivalent (stored in repo or organization secrets).

## 5. Step-by-Step Guide (Hands-on)

This example uses:
- GitHub Actions (YAML workflow)
- Node.js script to collect PRs and call the OpenAI Chat Completions API (HTTP fetch)
- Octokit REST API (via simple HTTP calls using GITHUB_TOKEN)

Prerequisites:
- A repository with releases or tags.
- Secrets set: OPENAI_API_KEY and GITHUB_TOKEN (the latter is provided automatically to workflows, but you may prefer a PAT for broader scopes).

### 1) Workflow: .github/workflows/release-notes.yml

```yaml
name: Generate AI Release Notes
on:
  release:
    types: [created]
  push:
    tags:
      - 'v*' # trigger on semantic version tags like v1.2.3

permissions:
  contents: write
  issues: write
  pulls: read

jobs:
  generate:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - name: Checkout
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Setup Node
        uses: actions/setup-node@v4
        with:
          node-version: '18'

      - name: Install dependencies
        run: npm ci

      - name: Generate Release Notes
        env:
          GITHUB_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}
          OPENAI_API_KEY: ${{ secrets.OPENAI_API_KEY }}
          GITHUB_EVENT_PATH: ${{ github.event_path }}
          GITHUB_REPOSITORY: ${{ github.repository }}
          GITHUB_REF: ${{ github.ref }}
        run: node scripts/generate-release-notes.js
```

### 2) Node script: scripts/generate-release-notes.js

```javascript
// Node 18+ recommended
import fs from 'fs';
import fetch from 'node-fetch';

// Minimal helper to call GitHub REST API
async function githubApi(path, body = null, method = 'GET') {
  const base = 'https://api.github.com';
  const resp = await fetch(base + path, {
    method,
    headers: {
      Authorization: `Bearer ${process.env.GITHUB_TOKEN}`,
      'User-Agent': 'release-notes-bot',
      Accept: 'application/vnd.github.v3+json'
    },
    body: body ? JSON.stringify(body) : undefined
  });
  return resp.json();
}

// Fetch merged PRs between two SHAs or since last release tag
async function collectMergedPRs(owner, repo, base, head) {
  // Use the pulls/merge commits approach: list PRs merged to base branch
  // For brevity, request recent PRs and filter by merge_commit_sha range.
  const pulls = await githubApi(`/repos/${owner}/${repo}/pulls?state=closed&per_page=100`);
  // Filter merged PRs and map needed fields
  return pulls
    .filter(p => p.merged_at && p.base && p.base.ref === 'main')
    .map(p => ({
      number: p.number,
      title: p.title,
      body: p.body || '',
      user: p.user?.login,
      labels: p.labels?.map(l => l.name)
    }));
}

// Prompt builder – keep prompts concise and structured
function buildPrompt(prs, repo) {
  const lines = prs.map(p => `- PR #${p.number} ${p.title} (by ${p.user})\n  labels: ${p.labels?.join(', ') || 'none'}\n  ${p.body.split('\n').slice(0,4).join(' ')}\n`);
  return `You are a release-notes writer. Summarize the following merged PRs into a short, reader-friendly release notes section for ${repo}. Output markdown sections: Highlights, Features, Fixes, Breaking changes (if any). Keep it concise and use bullets.\n\n${lines.join('\n')}`;
}

async function callOpenAI(prompt) {
  const url = 'https://api.openai.com/v1/chat/completions';
  const resp = await fetch(url, {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: {
      'Content-Type': 'application/json',
      Authorization: `Bearer ${process.env.OPENAI_API_KEY}`
    },
    body: JSON.stringify({
      model: 'gpt-4', // use an appropriate model you have access to
      messages: [
        { role: 'system', content: 'You summarize changelogs into concise release notes.' },
        { role: 'user', content: prompt }
      ],
      max_tokens: 600,
      temperature: 0.2
    })
  });
  const data = await resp.json();
  // Chat completion response path: choices[0].message.content
  return data.choices?.[0]?.message?.content || '';
}

async function createRelease(owner, repo, tagName, body) {
  // Create a release (or update if exists) using GitHub API
  const payload = { tag_name: tagName, name: tagName, body, draft: false, prerelease: false };
  return githubApi(`/repos/${owner}/${repo}/releases`, payload, 'POST');
}

async function main() {
  const repoFull = process.env.GITHUB_REPOSITORY; // owner/repo
  const [owner, repo] = repoFull.split('/');
  const tagRef = process.env.GITHUB_REF; // refs/tags/v1.2.3
  const tag = tagRef.split('/').pop();

  // Collect PRs (this simple approach gets recent merged PRs; refine for your repo)
  const prs = await collectMergedPRs(owner, repo);
  if (!prs.length) {
    console.log('No merged PRs found. Exiting.');
    return;
  }

  const prompt = buildPrompt(prs, repo);
  const notes = await callOpenAI(prompt);

  // Create GitHub release with generated notes
  const release = await createRelease(owner, repo, tag, notes);
  console.log('Release created:', release.html_url || release.id);
}

main().catch(err => {
  console.error(err);
  process.exit(1);
});
```

Notes and best practices in the script:
- Use narrow scopes for tokens. Prefer GITHUB_TOKEN for standard release creation.
- Keep temperature low so outputs are deterministic.
- Limit max_tokens to control cost and response size.
- Sanitize PR bodies to avoid prompt injection.

### 3) Improve reliability and structure
- Use a template system: request the model to return JSON with labeled sections (e.g., {"highlights":[],"features":[],"fixes":[]}). Then validate and render to markdown.
- Add human review step: open a draft release or PR instead of publishing automatically.
- Cache previous release tag to only include relevant PRs.

## 6. Use Cases (with emojis)

- 📦 Automated releases: publish release notes whenever a tag is pushed.
- 📝 Draft PRs: open a pull request with generated CHANGELOG edits for maintainers to review.
- 🔍 QA summaries: generate a short checklist of changed areas for QA teams.
- 📣 Stakeholder briefs: create an email-friendly summary for product or support teams.
- 🔗 Changelog enrichment: tag PRs into categories (feature/fix/docs) automatically.

## 7. Comparison (if applicable)

| Approach | Features | Pricing | Best for |
|---|---:|---|---|
| AI generator (this guide) | Automated natural-language summaries, customizable prompts, structured outputs | Cost depends on LLM provider (billed per token / request) | Teams wanting readable, context-aware notes
| Release Drafter (open-source) | Template-based drafts, label-driven grouping | Free / open source | Teams who prefer deterministic templates and label-based grouping
| Manual release notes | Full human control | Time cost only | Small projects or when legal/strict wording required

Pricing notes: do not assume specific dollar amounts for LLM usage — consult your chosen provider (OpenAI, Anthropic, etc.) for current rates.

## 8. Pros and Cons

Pros:
- Saves time: automates routine writing.
- Consistency: enforces a consistent style via prompts.
- Scalability: works across many repos once templated.

Cons:
- Cost: LLM API calls incur usage fees.
- Hallucination risk: models can invent details if prompts are ambiguous — always include source facts and validate outputs.
- Security: sending private data to third-party APIs requires compliance checks.

## 9. Common Mistakes / Pitfalls

- Sending raw PR or commit bodies without sanitization: remove secrets and tokens before prompting.
- Publishing automatically without review: prefer draft releases or PRs for human verification.
- Overly broad prompts: be explicit about structure, length, and tone to reduce hallucinations.
- Missing rate-limit handling: exponential backoff and retry logic mitigate transient API errors.
- Using a model without the right access or quota: confirm model availability and adjust fallback behavior.

## 10. Conclusion

Build an AI release notes generator with GitHub Actions to reduce the manual effort of writing release notes while preserving readability and structure. Start with a draft workflow that collects merged PRs, builds a compact prompt, calls an LLM, and creates a draft release. Keep humans in the loop, validate outputs, and secure secrets. Next steps:
- Prototype in a single repo using draft releases.
- Add JSON-structured responses from the model for deterministic parsing.
- Implement error handling and retries for production readiness.

Additional resources:
- GitHub Actions docs (official) for workflow triggers and permissions.
- Your chosen LLM provider docs for authentication and rate limits.

Primary keyword: Build an AI release notes generator with GitHub Actions

